From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background data on dengue in India were extracted from the
GIDEON software program:
- Several outbreaks of dengue or dengue-like illness were registered during
the 1960's. Epidemics were registered in Delhi during 1967, 1970, 1982 and
1988.
- The first epidemic of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) in this country
occurred Calcutta in 1963, with a second wave of DHF in Visakapattnam in
1965. A total of 1,948 cases were officially recorded in 1976; 57,607 in
1982. 6,291 cases of DHF (3 fatal) were reported in 1991; 2,683 (12) in
1992; 11,125 (36) in 1993; 7,494 (4) in 1994; 7,847 (10) in 1995; 13,069
(460) in 1996.
- Epidemics of dengue were registered in the northwest in 1985; and in the
south (Tamil Nadu) in 1990. 128 cases of DHF (28 fatal) were reported
during 1986 to 1990. An estimated 800 cases occurred in Calcutta in 1990.
- 10,234 cases of dengue and DHF (mortality 4.13%) were registered in Delhi
during 1996, with additional cases in Rajasthan and Uttar Pradesh.
--
Steve Berger
Tel Aviv Medical Center
